urchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance (MR) imaging are increasingly important adjuncts to echocardiography for the evaluation of mitral valve disease. The mitral valve may be involved in various acquired or congenital conditions with resultant regurgitation or stenosis, and many of these conditions can be identified with CT or MR imaging. In addition, CT is useful for detecting and monitoring postoperative complications after mitral valve repair or replacement. As the use of CT and MR imaging increases, awareness of the CT and MR imaging appearances of the normal mitral valve and the various disease processes that affect it may foster recognition of unsuspected mitral disease in patients undergoing imaging for other purposes. Supplemental material available at <i><supplementary-material>http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.306105518/-/DC1</supplementary-material></i></div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2010</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.306105518">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.306105518">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig01a.jpeg" height="938" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig01a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig01b.jpeg" height="939" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig01b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig02.jpeg" height="1800" width="1780" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Normal imaging appearance of the mitral valve. Short-axis maximum intensity projection image from contrast material–enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in a 61-year-old man shows the straight anterior (black arrow) and curved posterior (black arrowhead) portions of the normal mitral annulus. White arrow = coronary sinus, white arrow-head = left circumflex artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig03.jpeg" height="1131" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Photograph of a short-axis section from the base of a healthy human heart with the atria removed shows normal appearances of the aortic (<i>AV</i>), mitral (<i>MV</i>), pulmonic (<i>PV</i>), and tricuspid (<i>TV</i>) valves during simulated ventricular diastole. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig04.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig04" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Short-axis diastolic image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in a 63-year-old man shows normal anterior (A1, A2, A3) and posterior (P1, P2, P3) mitral valve leaflets, which are composed of lateral (A1, P1), middle (A2, P2), and medial (A3, P3) segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig04">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1798" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1793" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig06.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Three-chamber systolic image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging in a 46-year-old man shows bileaflet mitral prolapse (arrows) and a dephasing jet from mitral regurgitation (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig07.jpeg" height="1564" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Short-axis diastolic image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64- channel CT in a 68-year-old man shows a P2 segment mitral prolapse (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig08.jpeg" height="1108" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Photograph of a short-axis section from the base of the heart of a 76-year-old woman, with the atria cut away, shows thickened and rubbery mitral leaflets with prominent bileaflet prolapse. Arrow = P2 segment. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig09.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Three-chamber systolic image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in a 57-year-old man shows a thickened posterior mitral leaflet with a flail P2 segment (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig10.jpeg" height="1280" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Photograph of a long-axis section (three-chamber view) from the heart of a 70-year-old woman shows a ruptured anterolateral papillary muscle and a flail anterior mitral leaflet (arrow). (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig11a.jpeg" height="1570" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig11b.jpeg" height="1589" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig12.jpeg" height="1778" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Three-chamber systolic view from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging in a 32-year-old man with hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy shows a posteriorly directed dephasing jet of mitral regurgitation (arrow) and signal dephasing due to high flow through the left ventricular outflow tract (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig13.jpeg" height="1280" width="791" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Photograph of a long-axis section from the left heart of a day-old male infant with hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy shows thickened myocardium in close proximity to the anterior mitral leaflet (arrow), simulating an obstruction of the left ventricular outflow tract. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig14.jpeg" height="1431" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Short-axis diastolic view from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64- channel CT in a 62-year-old woman with rheumatic mitral stenosis shows thickening of the mitral valve leaflets (arrows) with commissural fusion and calcification (arrowhead), features that produce a characteristic “fish-mouth” appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig15.jpeg" height="1024" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Photograph of a short-axis section from the base of the heart of a 44-year-old woman with rheumatic mitral stenosis shows diffuse fibrous leaflet thickening (arrow) and commissural fusion (arrowhead) that cause the valve to resemble a fish mouth. A large anteroseptal myocardial infarction with associated mural attenuation also is depicted. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig16.jpeg" height="1534" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Two-chamber diastolic view from ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging in a 74-year-old woman with rheumatic mitral stenosis shows anterior leaflet thickening and bowing (arrow), which produces a “hockey-stick” appearance. The posterior leaflet is also thickened (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig17.jpeg" height="1087" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Photograph of a long-axis section (three-chamber view) from the heart of a 55-year-old woman with rheumatic mitral stenosis shows prominent thickening of the mitral leaflets and chordae, with associated bowing of the anterior leaflet (arrow) producing the characteristic hockey-stick appearance. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig18.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Axial diastolic image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in an 80-year-old woman shows leaflet calcifications (arrows), a cause of mitral stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig19.jpeg" height="1260" width="1218" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Axial diastolic image from contrast-enhanced 16-channel CT in a 71-year-old woman shows a left atrial myxoma (arrow) obstructing mitral inflow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig20.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Photograph of a long-axis cardiac section (three-chamber view) shows a large myxoma arising from the left atrial septum and blocking the mitral orifice (arrow). (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig21.jpeg" height="1500" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Short-axis diastolic view from ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging performed for planimetry in a 67-year-old woman shows mild mitral stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig22a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig22b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1798" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig23.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Caseous degeneration of the mitral annulus in an 86-year-old woman. Four-chamber view from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated 64- channel multidetector CT shows a mass in the posterior aspect of the annulus (arrow). The mass is demarcated by a peripheral enhancing rim of calcification and contains a central region of lesser hyperattenuation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig24.jpeg" height="853" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Photograph of a long-axis section (three-chamber view) from the heart of a 79-year-old man shows calcification and caseous degeneration of the posterior aspect of the mitral annulus (arrowhead) and left ventricular hypertrophy due to aortic stenosis. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig25a.jpeg" height="1368" width="1334" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig25b.jpeg" height="1088" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig26.jpeg" height="1627" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Short-axis view from ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging in a 36-year-old man with a partial atrioventricular canal defect shows an anterior mitral leaflet cleft (arrow) directed toward the septum. An atrial septal defect was previously repaired.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig27.jpeg" height="1647" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span> Three-chamber view from ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging in a 20-year-old woman shows all the chordae arising from the posteromedial papillary muscle (arrow), a finding that represents a parachute mitral valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig28.jpeg" height="1522" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span> Short-axis view from ECG-gated 1.5-T SSFP MR imaging in a 49-year-old man shows a double-orifice mitral valve (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig29.jpeg" height="1043" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span> Photograph (left atrial view) shows a bridge of leaflet tissue that crosses the mitral valve annulus, creating a double orifice (arrows). (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Department of Pathology, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig30.jpeg" height="1800" width="1717" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span> Short-axis view from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT after surgical repair of mitral valve prolapse in a 68-year-old man shows a 63-mm posterior annuloplasty band (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig31.jpeg" height="1085" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span> Intraoperative photograph obtained with a high-definition robotic camera shows the placement of a 63-mm flexible posterior annuloplasty band after P2 segment resection and suture reconstruction for treatment of mitral valve prolapse.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig32.jpeg" height="1800" width="1660" aria-labelledby="fig32" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32</span> Short-axis image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT at the level of the mitral annulus in a 63-year-old woman shows a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) arising from a bioprosthetic mitral valve (arrowhead). An adjacent aortic valve prosthesis (black arrow) also is depicted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig32">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig33.jpeg" height="1800" width="1691" aria-labelledby="fig33" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33</span> Malfunctioning bileaflet mitral valve prosthesis. Four-chamber diastolic view from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in a 60-year-old woman shows that the anterior mitral leaflet remains closed (arrow) while the posterior leaflet is open (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig33">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig34.jpeg" height="1780" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig34" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34</span> Two-chamber view from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in a 58-year-old man after mitral valve repair shows partial dehiscence of a posterior annuloplasty band (arrow), most of which remains in the appropriate position in the atrioventricular groove (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig34">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105518/asset/images/105518fig35.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig35" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35</span> Short-axis maximum intensity projection image from contrast-enhanced ECG-gated dual-source 64-channel CT in a 39-year-old man after mitral valve repair shows a posterior annuloplasty band impinging on a left circumflex artery stent (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105518&amp;id=fig35">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Ho SY. Anatomy of the mitral valve. <em>Heart</em> 2002;88(suppl 4):iv5–iv10.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/heart.88.suppl_4.iv5">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12369589/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Anatomy+of+the+mitral+valve&amp;author=SY+Ho&amp;publication_year=2002&amp;journal=Heart&amp;pages=iv5-iv10&amp;doi=10.1136%2Fheart.88.suppl_4.iv5&amp;pmid=12369589">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Nkomo VT, Gardin JM, Skelton TN, Gottdiener JS, Scot